2. Turn the square upside down.
3. Have the edge between tourquiose and white on the small square allign with the same edge on the big square.

Because you flipped the small square, tourquiose is now right of white while in the original, it was left of right.

10a + b - (a+b) = 9a

I read that all integers can be paired with all even Integers just by x paired with 2x, proving that they are lists of equal size, but I don't know if primes could match up that easily. Mainly because the list of all known prime numbers is finite(the highest recorded is  Mersenne prime M74207481) and prime numbers can't be evaluated into a series or a function in general. idk I was just curious as to your thoughts. thank you for your time.",1,true,1,,,,,,
,,,,,,,,default-z12qyfvhbqygsdhab04cjxcpfrnucv2ggzg0k.1493656810512467,AddressError,1 week ago,1494236952290,"All we need is a function that gives a different prime for every integer n. There is one based on Mills' constant: f(n) = floor(Œ∏^3^n), where Œ∏ is the Mills' constant, a number approximately equal to 1.30637... (assuming the Riemann hypothesis is true, although the constant with the properties has been proven to exist regardless). Therefore, we can map integers 1, 2, 3, 4, 5... to f(1), f(2), f(3), f(4), f(5)... (which happen to be 2, 11, 1361, 2521008887, 16022236204009818131831320183...). This proves that this subset of prime numbers has the same cardinality as integers (aleph null), and therefore the set of all primes must have the same cardinality as well (if the prime cardinality was greater, there would be more primes than integers, which doesn't make any sense since the set of all primes is a subset of all integers, and if the prime set cardinality would be less, our subset of primes would have a greater cardinality than it, which also doesn't make any sense).",0

,,,,,,,,z12yfdtxuznxzfsak04cjb0gkmfhfjspcl40k.1487754192981339,chaosmeister,2 months ago,1489571370108,"I think you misunderstood Cantor's argument. He proved that no matter how you arrange (count) the real numbers, there are always real numbers left that you didn't count.  Hence the real numbers are of a different magnitude than the natural (counting) numbers.  And hence there is indeed something beyond the simple ""1, 2, many, infinite"" infinity of the natural numbers -- an even ""bigger infinity"". So yes, the ""actual size of the infinity"" of the real numbers is bigger than that of the natural numbers.",0

,,,,,,,,default-z13dzroqmpmofnpd022cexwywzj2cpudx.1486831880438467,MuffinsAPlenty,3 months ago,1487152173692,"Yes.  For any positive integer N, in base N+1, taking any number with more than one digit, if you keep adding the digits together and subtracting that sum, then you will eventually end with N.  In other words, if you follow the same procedure in binary, you'll always end with a 1.  If you follow the same procedure in octal, you'll always end with a 7, etc.

The sketch of the proof is as follows: in base N+1 notation, if you subtract the sum of the digits from any positive whole number with more than one digit, then you will get a multiple of N.  Moreover, taking any multiple of N with more than one digit in base N+1, the sum of the digits is a strictly smaller but positive multiple of N.

So the basic idea goes like this.  You take your starting number, and subtract the sum of its digits.  You get a multiple of N.  Now, you add those digits together and subtract that, and you'll get a strictly smaller but nonzero multiple of N.  Continue this way if you still have a number with more than one digit.  Since there are only finitely many multiples of N smaller than any given multiple of N, this process must terminate.  Moreover, when it terminates, the result is strictly positive.  However, if you have more than one digit, then you can continue the process.  Thus, we see that this process must end with a positive single-digit number which is a multiple of N.  There is only one possibility here: N itself.",0

The trick is to see that after a certain point, the words used to represent a number will always have fewer letters than the value of the number itself.  It's pretty clear that this is true for numbers above twenty, for example.  Therefore, if you pick a big enough number, you will quickly find yourself having a small number of letters.  Then, you just have to show that the process works for all small enough numbers, and it does.",0

That example has a limit to how much you decrease it in size, if you make the overlapping piece of paper smaller then 1 square of the original it becomes quite easy. Hence now that you are only the size of  1 piece you only have one color overlapping, but if you were to flip the paper and put it on the boundary of one of its neighbors and make sure that the same corresponding boundary in the smaller paper lines up with the boundary of the larger piece, you will see it miraculously never light up at all.

z131xtfbwmbgs3sux22auh1ggqaofn4hy04,Legoboy,5 months ago,1481795411052,"Thinking about the ""attractive nine"" fixed point, you can do this trick with any number to find if it is divisible by something, just write the number out in a bass of one more than the factor you are checking. For example, I could check if sixteen is divisible by eight (it is, of course) by writing it in base nine: 17, or one nine and seven ones. 1+7=8, which is divisible by eight, so sixteen is divisible by eight. This is much more useful, especially with small numbers, for checking whether something is divisible by eight than the rule of ""if the last three digits are divisible by eight, then the number is divisible by eight.""",1,false,0,,,,,,

,,,,,,,,z130wxmiakqmjrayd04cjbco2za0s3sqa24.1481464955206303,Rajarshi Bandopadhyay,5 months ago,1481795416798,"+Jacob Beckey
¬†Yes, roughly. Its original use was for deriving square roots in Babylon, China and India in ancient times. Heron systematized it into an algorithm step by step.
Newton and Rhapson did not generalize it. They accidentally derived the general case while working on Numerical analysis. They came up with a method to quickly converge on the solution of f(x) = 0, and putting f(x) = x^2-a, you get the square root of a. z12bex0aalr0vbbtj23yt3xpctedctlh004,Alex Rodi,5 months ago,1481795416429,"Great video! as always...

here's something interesting i found out once in a math class and could never forget:

count 180¬∫ from 0¬∫:
0, 180, 360, 540, 720, 900

Now count 180¬∫ from 90¬∫:
90, 270, 450, 630, 810

Get it? The order is reversed if you swap the numbers before the last 0

180->810
360->630
540->450

z12iu10qepaktraje04cdlqxsvakshnxgpo0k,Global Warming Skeptic,6 months ago,1479203424273,"The problem with antipodal points is more of a problem with how we logically apply mathematics.  Clearly, two  antipodal points that have no connection other than the same body as one another wouldn't necessarily have to have anything to do with one another.

And I think this is where we get into problems with continuous numbers, because you can come up with a million absurd statements similar where, if you assume that distance, time, temperature, and the like are thought of as continuous curves.

You don't even need antipodal points.  You can say that two points within your house must be exactly the same temperature and pressure as one another as well.  

This is why each measurement should be seen as its own individual reading with a certain margin of error attached.  Graphing such measurements can give useful information about cause, effect or correlation if nothing else, but once you start applying functional curves to reality, that's when you run into absurdity.",0,false,0,,,,,,

Proof is: consider the¬†(admitedly continuous) surface of the floor, and imagine you glue three table legs to it. The fourth is then sticking up, at a positive altitude. z13qj1jyolvtir1ha04cflj5em3ht5f4pck,theawsome,6 months ago,1479203477852,"3 pounds mixed apples (such as Granny Smith, Gala and McIntosh)
2/3 cup granulated sugar
2 tablespoons fresh lemon juice
6 tablespoons unsalted butter
1 tablespoon all-purpose flour, plus more for dusting
3/4 teaspoon ground cinnamon
1/8 teaspoon salt
2 disks dough for Basic Crust 
1 large egg, beaten
Coarse sugar, for sprinkling

Peel and core the apples; slice 1/4 inch thick. Toss with the granulated sugar and lemon juice. Heat 4 tablespoons butter in a large skillet over medium-high heat. Add the apples and cook, stirring, until tender, about 10 minutes. Stir in the flour, cinnamon and salt; cook until thickened, 1 more minute. Let cool.

Roll out 1 disk of dough into a 12-inch round on a floured surface; ease into a 9-inch pie plate. Add the apples, mounding them slightly in the center, and dot with the remaining 2 tablespoons butter. Roll out the remaining dough into a 12-inch round. Lay it over the filling; press the edges of the crusts together, then fold the overhang under itself and crimp to seal. Brush with the beaten egg and sprinkle with coarse sugar. Cut a few slits in the top crust. Chill 1 hour.

Place a baking sheet on the lowest oven rack and preheat to 425 degrees F for 30 minutes. Place the pie on the hot baking sheet; lower the temperature to 375 degrees F. Bake until golden, 1 hour to 1 hour, 10 minutes. (Cover the edges with foil if they brown too quickly.) Cool on a rack",0,false,0,,,,,,

,,,,,,,,z12dglrgzwjsif1oz04cexkwbteugtwyvhs.1480824305901924,Wayne Stakem,5 months ago,1481795478146,"I had to Google the Mandela effect because I never heard of it. I thought it was ""No, Luke, I am your father"" because I distinctly remembered there being no. But apparently a lot of others thought it was just ""Luke, I am your father"". Austin Powers 

Austin Powers (Mike Myers) shoots the running Dr. Evil in his spacesuit. He turns to Austin and says (with a voice similar to Vader's): ""But, before you kill me... know this... Austin... I am your father"".

Speed Racer: The Next Generation

When Connor says that it's a coincidence that Speed has Speed Racer's things and implies that he might be a relative, Speed replies, ""I have as much of a chance of being related to Speed Racer as you do of being a relative of Darth Vader."" Robot Chim-Chim puts a bucket on Connor's head and Connor immitates Darth Vader's breathing and says, ""Speed, I am your father.

Tommy Boy (1995) 

‚ÄùAt one point Tommy (Chris Farley) says, ""Luke, I am your father"" into a fan, which makes his voice sound mechanical.‚Äù

Toy Story 2

Later in the movie, Buzz Lightyear II accuses Emperor Zurg of killing his father. Then, Zurg reveals that he is Buzz's father: ""No, Buzz, I am your father,"" as Buzz screams ""Noooooo!"" while descending down the elevator. By the end of the film, they're playing together and experiencing lots of good father-son bonding.

,,,,,,,,z13af1zhetn4vdnqz04cf3lydxblwdpwxjk.1477143564146694,obviouslycookies,6 months ago,1479203479693,"Well, let me try to explain.

So what you said is obviously true. BUT when you scale down the whole board to be smaller then a square,it becomes very possible.
so take your really small board and place it in the bottom right corner, say its gray. Obviously you'll have the gray square of the small board that glows. but then here's what you do. flip the board 180 degrees and place it so that your small little gray square (that is now on the top left of your small board) and the whole vertical line it is in right outside the big gray square, like, right against it.
So what you end up is, the small checkerboard overlapping two big squares. lets say the other big square is yellow. well basically, the small checkerboard will be mostly on a big gray square, but the actual little gray square and the column he is in will be on the big yellow square.
but what about the small yellow square, where is he at? well if you do this and make it so that the little gray square is right against the big gray square, you'll find that the small yellow square is on the big gray square, right against the big yellow square. If you do this just right  nothing will glow and no rules have been broken.

Now this is very hard to explain verbally, as you can see, But i am pretty positive that what i'm saying is true.

But how do you explain this because Micheal obviously said that whatever you do, one point of the checkerboard will, no matter what, stay right where it began right ?

Well turns out this stays true. its just that the checkerboard is not such a great example at the end of the day. Because the point that has not moved in the scenario I created right above, is a point that is perfectly on the line between the yellow and the gray squares.

now if you did not understand what i tried to explain, its okay. Again, its very hard to explain something visual in just a YouTube comment. 

(sorry for the spelling errors and such, i'm not a native English speaker..)

All that said, if you read until this point, have a great day!

While it would be true that there must be a point that retains its original position, it is quite easy to move every pixel into a position outside of its original square; for example, rotate the grid by 180¬∞ and align so that two squares that are next to each other in the original grid are on opposite sides of the line between them, and shrink the new grid to fit within the old one. There will be a point on the line between those two squares that is a 'fixed point,' but no pixel.

z13mxrtqjqalzzer504cg1q4kvuqffzozm00k,Leo Moran,7 months ago,1476525128037,"""At any given moment, there must be at least one pair of points on Earth's surface, that are diametrically opposite one another, but nonetheless have the same temperature and atmospheric pressure.""
That statement made in the video (9:38) is, in fact, almost always FALSE.

Here's why:
While it is demonstrably true that at least one pair of points diametrically opposed on Earth's surface (antipodes) must have the same temperature, and it is demonstrably true that at least one pair of antipodes must have the same atmospheric pressure... what is not demonstrably true is that the antipodes that have the same temperature also has the same atmospheric pressure, or vice versa.  Atmospheric pressure and temperature are NOT functionally dependent upon one another.

What is true is:
There are always two antipodes where temperature are the same, and there are always two antipodes where pressure are the same, but they are not necessarily the same pair of antipodes.... the statement in the video was that there is always a pair of antipodes where temperature AND pressure are the same.",0,true,1,,,,,,
,,,,,,,,default-z13mxrtqjqalzzer504cg1q4kvuqffzozm00k.1475825690533089,PirateOfPlayTime,7 months ago,1476525128041,"Take what he's saying at 11:18. 
You take two thermometers and measure the temperature at two points on exact opposite sides of the earth, then switch their places while keeping them on opposite sides of the earth from each other and graph the temperatures they both record. You'd find that no matter how you move them across the earth to switch their locations (of course except that both thermometers must be on opposite sides of the planet), the graph of their temperatures must intersect somewhere. So you'd find that at all times there is not just one pair of points, but an entire line going around the earth where the temperature is the same on both sides of the earth (the line at 12:08). 
Then, take two barometers and place them at two antipodes that are on that line and switch their locations and make a graph of the air pressures they record. At some point, the two lines on the pressure graph would intersect just as the two lines on the temperature graph did. Thus, on the line of all antipodes where temperature is the same, one pair of them has the same air pressure as well.",9

z13guxlpdu2bzhtr204ce14bsojxsxtalqs0k,Jim Ramirez,7 months ago,1476525145966,What about elevation? There's not always another point as high as the tallest peak. Is elevation not continuous in the same sense? What about a super hot spot for that matter? The hottest place currently on earth? There's not going to be another spot as hot if it's the hottest.,0,true,1,,,,,,
,,,,,,,,default-z13guxlpdu2bzhtr204ce14bsojxsxtalqs0k.1475639097155739,MuffinsAPlenty,7 months ago,1476525145973,"""What about elevation? There's not always another point as high as the tallest peak. Is elevation not continuous in the same sense?""

No, elevation is not continuous.  There are jumps in elevation between certain points.  For instance, look at the walls of the Grand Canyon.  Sure, some parts are sloped, but other parts of large drop-offs, making elevation discontinuous.

But even if elevation were discontinuous, the fact that there is only one ""highest point on Earth"" would not invalidate the theorem just as much as there being only one ""hottest place on Earth"" doesn't invalidate the theorem.

The theorem makes no claim about what the temperature at those two antipodal points (which have the same temperature) is.  It never says that there are two antipodal points which are also the hottest point on Earth.  It just says that those two points have the same temperature.  Similarly, if I were to say that there are two antipodal points on Earth which have the same elevation, that would not imply that those two points are the highest points on Earth.",0

,,,,,,,,z12yepsxbm20xjtfe22kyfk5imqtib54u04.1476754727546025,tory mountain,6 months ago,1479203555784,"I trust you understand why I asked you to look up the word I called you. 

Here are several dubious (painfully unscientific) sources for your beloved '97%' figure:

1.  One frequently cited source for the consensus is a 2004 opinion essay published in Science magazine by Naomi Oreskes, a science historian. She claimed to have examined abstracts of 928 articles published in scientific journals between 1993 & 2003, and found that 75% supported the view that human activities are responsible for most of the observed warming over the previous 50 years while none directly dissented.  Ms. Oreskes's definition of consensus covered ""man-made"" but left out ""dangerous"".  Scores of articles by prominent scientists such as Richard Lindzen, John Christy, Sherwood Idso and Patrick Michaels, who question the consensus, were excluded (!) 

2.  Another widely cited source for the consensus view is a 2009 article in ""Eos, Transactions American Geophysical Union"" by Maggie Kendall Zimmerman, a student at the University of Illinois and her master's thesis adviser Peter Doran. It reported the results of a two-question online survey of selected scientists. Mr. Doran & Ms. Zimmerman claimed ""97 percent of climate scientists agree"" that global temperatures have risen and that humans are a significant contributing factor. The survey's questions don't reveal much of interest. Most scientists who are skeptical of catastrophic global warming nevertheless would answer ""yes"" to both questions. The survey was silent on whether the human impact is large enough to constitute a problem. Nor did it include solar scientists, space scientists, etc.  The ""97%"" figure in the Zimmerman/Doran survey represents the views of only 79 respondents who listed climate science as an area of expertise and said they published more than half of their recent peer-reviewed papers on climate change. Seventy-nine scientists‚Äîof the 3,146 (!) who responded to the survey‚Äîdoes not a consensus make.""

(You cite:) 

3. In 2010, William R. Love Anderegg, then a student at Stanford University, used Google Scholar to identify the views of the most prolific writers on climate change.  His findings were published in Proceedings of the National Academies of Sciences. Mr. Anderegg found that 97% to 98% of the 200 most prolific writers on climate change believe ""anthropogenic greenhouse gases have been responsible for 'most' of the 'unequivocal' warming."" There was no mention of how dangerous this climate change might be; and, of course, 200 researchers out of the thousands who have contributed to the climate science debate is not evidence of consensus.

4. In 2013, John Cook, an Australia-based blogger, and some of his friends reviewed abstracts of peer-reviewed papers published from 1991 to 2011. Mr. Cook reported that 97% of those who stated a position explicitly or implicitly suggest that human activity is responsible for some warming. His findings were published in Environmental Research Letters.  Mr. Cook's work was quickly debunked...."" 

Summary:

""Of the various petitions on global warming circulated for signatures by scientists, the one by the Petition Project, a group of physicists and physical chemists based in La Jolla, Calif., has by far the most signatures‚Äîmore than 31,000 (more than 9,000 with a Ph.D.). It was most recently published in 2009, and most signers were added or reaffirmed since 2007. The petition states that ""there is no convincing scientific evidence that human release of . . . carbon dioxide, methane, or other greenhouse gases is causing or will, in the foreseeable future, cause catastrophic heating of the Earth's atmosphere and disruption of the Earth's climate.""

We could go on, but the larger point is plain. There is no basis for the claim that 97% of scientists believe that man-made climate change is a dangerous problem.""",0

¬†Just ignore the pixel example. It was a bad example.
¬†With pixels, it is possible to break the definition. With a continuous shape of an indefinite number of points (inside the shape), it is not. This is because the pixel sheet has a defined number of points.

¬†As such, there is no issue with the idea/theorem/what-have-you.

,,,,,,,,z12igzqrpsjwirwag04chltwsrj1g345pj4.1476651886422886,anticorncob6,6 months ago,1479203563877,"+Brad Gefroh If you consider the pixels to be solid, then you can realign all the points elsewhere.
If you assign a color to each point in a continuous square then no continuous transformation that remains in the square can send every point to one of a different color. Borders (sets of points that are not contained in a circle of finite radius all of which are solidly that color) must exist, and you have not defined what it means to ""align"" them. You cannot get rid of them.
The only way to ""break"" the theorem is to apply it to a context it is not designed for. If you are seriously going to argue that the Borsuk-Ulam theorem is false then you can send your counter-example to a university, become famous, and leave mathematicians going mad trying to find the errors in the proof (as a bonus you can point the error out to them). But that is not going to happen.",0

tldr; Temperature jumps from atom to atom, ALWAYS, so there will ALWAYS be JUMPS in the graph he showed, meaning it won't pass through each other when it flips, it will JUMP PAST each other.

To explain why he's wrong. Lets look at temperature, the fact that the temperate EVER changes anywhere on earth proves that there was a jump in temperature. If it is 1 degrees on point A and 2 on point B, then somewhere, between point A and B, there was a jump in temperature, unless point A and B are an INFINITE distance away, which is not the case when it comes to earth. The only way for a continues string of variables along a sphere to be perfectly containing of every single inbetween temperature of 1 and 2 is for either for every point on the sphere to be the same temperature already, or for the sphere to be infinitely large. 


As you may have seen him explain on his ""how to count past infinity"" video, there are Infinite digits between 1 and 2, therefore Infinite possible temperatures, there fore on earth there is always a point where when temperature changes, there is a jump in temperature change. A JUMP, not a incline, there fore the two points you flipped can JUMP at any point and will technically jump at EVERY SINGLE point. 


The same is for atmospheric pressure, there will always be JUMPS in pressure, making his little explanation wrong. 


If it were a sphere with infinite locations in a theoretical world, maybe. but on earth, it's just 100% incorrect to make that assumption.


Now someone might go ahead and say """"There are infinite points, which are infinitely small, between point A and point B, therefore it could change at a rate instead of jumps"""", which is wrong, because temperature varies ATOM to ATOM, and JUMPS ATOM to ATOM, so, in this universe. z12ycvq4mqvlt5psd22xyt1xqnzwtriwr04,Alexander Demetrius,7 months ago,1476525170587,"Hello, for no reason in particular I wanted to ask anyone who is good at probability and numbers to disprove my logic stating that ""infinite"" is impossible. I just wanted someone to disprove this because I think a lot, keep getting stuck on this point and no one seems to want to listen to me.

Infinite has an intrinsic probability. For example if a light has two settings (on, off) that means there is a 1 in 2 chance it is on and 1 in 2 chance it is off. 0.5 probability. If there are two lights with two settings there are one in four chances the first will be on and the second off. 0.25 probability. If there are infinite lights and infinite settings that means there is a 1 over 1 chance they are all on. 1 probability. This doesn't seem to make sense as there is 100% chance they are both all on and all off. You could also say it like this. If there are infinite universes there is 100% chance there is one that you can travel to all universes from and 100% chance there is a universe that cannot be traveled to even though they cannot logically coexist.

z13uxfngzuqle323z23thj35pufahrhco,Kisama,7 months ago,1476525183258,"Bah. That theorum(in regards to Earth) assumes that you can't go from one point to another without the temperature/pressure raising/dropping in spikes. In other words: the temperature in point A and the temperature in point B drops 2 degrees, not 1. If you use exact points on the graph, instead of line, then no, this theory just falls apart. In fact, the further your degree of accuracy goes, the more unlikely it is that you will ever see two opposite points on earth with the same temperature, or the same pressure.

This theory for Earth only holds if you graph using a straight line instead of pinpoint accuracy. 
Example: Point A was 13.659 degrees on both sides of the Earth, but no matter what, there was no Point B that was 13.659c, 13.658c, or 13.660c, simply because the temperature of the very next atom nearby on at least one side was 13.661c, while the other side was 13.657c. 
Or, the very next atom was .000000000000000000001m to the left/right/up/down of it's counterpart. 
Or, there was no atom at all to counterpoint, just the vacuum between loosely packed atoms, which is more likely if the surface is water. 

The theory for the coffee cup is also misleading: there are infinitely more places for atoms of coffee to exist than there are atoms in the cup. Even by a degree of movement as small as the fraction of a fraction of an electron's quark, the chance that EVERY ATOM will be somewhere new and not occupying any previously existing place EXACTLY (the most exact atom could still be 1 degree tilted on the z axis differently than before mixing) is infinitesimal. 

The theory CAN be true for these examples, simply due to probability, or by looseness of definition. But the more exact you make your definitions, the less likely it will occur, if ever.",0,false,0,,,,,,

z123ihwjitj1vbcyt04cdb5puky2yr3ibv00k,Jesse Clark,7 months ago,1476525216113,"Imagine that I have a car filled with balloons. This car has a lemniscate (the sideways 8 that represents infinity) on the licence plate. The number of balloons in that car cannot be counted. It is literally impossible to count them. One might come along and say ""Well, they all fit in one car. Imagine if we changed that license plate to a different symbol and put a zero beside it. Now imagine if you had two cars (with the same symbol plus 1), or three, or an uncountable number of them. And what if the uncountable number of them is on a car carrier? And there are multiple car carriers?"" To which I would reply ""You can't have more than one car full of them because the ones in the car already can't be counted. Another car full of the same number can't exist, because this one already contains all of the balloons that there can be in a car.""

We already have a variable for infinity (the aforementioned sideways 8), which you can't do anything with because it's infinite. Changing the variable, then adding to that variable, is impossible, because the first variable by necessity must already contain every countable number. That would have to include aleph 1, aleph 2, etc. because they can be counted.",0,false,0,,,,,,

If you move through space very quickly, or are under the influence of extreme gravitational forces you will seemingly experience time at a slower rate than someone who is not. In your own individual frames of reference you wouldn't notice anything unusual, and would both say that time is behaving normally. But if you slowed down and returned to this person your clock would say that less time has passed than your theirs would. 

This occurs because the speed of light is fixed, and all observers must agree on it despite discrepancies within their reference frames. In other words: General relativity is confusing and I'm not nearly a good enough mathematician to test the equations myself so I just accept it as true because it has been proven as such.",0

z121tl5z4qakuvu1v234vpkwppj2szzb004,dambien,7 months ago,1476525227789,"I'm kinda surprised he didn't also mention Kaprekar's constant (6174). This number is neat. Here's how it works:

1. Take any 4 digit number that isn't just 4 identical numbers (for example, 9999 won't work). Let's use 8593.
2. Reorder the numbers from largest to smallest - 9853.
3. Reorder the numbers from smallest to largest - 3589.
4. Subtract the number in step 3 from the number in step 2. 9853-3589 = 6264
5. Repeat steps 2-4 with the same number and record the result:
5a.  6642-2466 = 4176
5b.  7641-1467 = 6174
5c.  7641-1467 = 6174

You'll notice that no matter which 4 digits you choose, as long as they're not all the same digit, you'll eventually reach 6174 and it will keep looping forever. This is Kaprekar's constant.

I believe that is where your idea is flawed.. I can understand why you would consider molecules to be discrete, and they are.. But matter is considered to be continuous and as such, this continuity leads to the generation of fixed points..",0

z135v1vzin2xsxe3y230j1d5jnahd5yv5,Charles Brightman,7 months ago,1476525252170,"1, 3, 6, 9:
1 photon with
3 components  (Electrical, Magnetic, Direction) all basically 90 degrees from each other,
each component having an oscillation of energy,
maximum in one direction, neutral, maximum in the other direction.

So:
Electrical : max in one direction, neutral, max in the other direction;
Magnetic : max in one direction, neutral, max in the other direction;
Direction  : max in one direction, neutral, max in the other direction.
(The direction of a stationary photon is a pulse.  It goes to it's central core area, then flips and goes to it's max extension area, then flips, etc, etc, etc);

6 maximum most reactive positions with
9 total reactive positions (neutrals included).
Hence 1, 3, 6, 9 being very prominent numbers in our math systems.

And, if it were taken further: 1 + 3 + 6 + 9 = 19
1 + 9 = 10
1 + 0 = 1, back to the 1 photon.",0,false,0,,,,,,

,,,,,,,,z12uuhezipb3ydxa104chj2ruz2pfzhbhas.1475297410054980,Evelyn Finegan,7 months ago,1476525257472,"+Thomas Riley that still wouldn't work because to do that you're moving molecules from the top down to the bottom simultaneously, because they have to make room for the new molecules from the bottom. You're still causing a translation of the coffee, you can think of it like you're still causing it to rotate/spin, only instead of rotating around an axis that goes through the center of the coffee (as you do by traditional stirring), you're now just rotating along an axis that goes horizontally through the coffee mug. And if you're just pulling molecules up from the bottom, well that's equivalent to starting your spoon at one antipode and moving it to the opposite antipode, only instead of along the X or Z axis you're now using the Y axis. As long as all of the molecules of the coffee mug start and end within the confines of the mug, then you have got a fixed point at which at least one molecule is in the same, within a certain degree of accuracy, position as when it started.",3

,,,,,,,,z12uuhezipb3ydxa104chj2ruz2pfzhbhas.1475338438909866,Thomas Riley,7 months ago,1476525257492,"+Herr Schmidt No, it shouldn't, because coffee is a Newtonian liquid, meaning it has wave-like behavior, and splashes.",0
,,,,,,,,z12uuhezipb3ydxa104chj2ruz2pfzhbhas.1475353725417162,Docteur Zeuhl,7 months ago,1476525257494,"Math teacher here. (French, so... sorry for bad english, I guess.)
Mixing coffee is not a continuous transformation because coffee itself, being made of molecules, is technically not a continuous medium. Brouwer's theorem applies only to continuous medium. You could actually think about ""rearranging"" all the molecules in your coffee, one by one, so that the ""first"" one goes in ""second"" place, the ""second"" one in ""third"" place, and so on, with any order that you arbitrarily chose. However, if you randomly choose, in an urn full of all molecules, which one will take the first spot, then which one takes the second spot, and so on, these very particular ""nothing matching"" arrangements are way less probable than arrangements in which no single molecule is in its initial place, which you can see as a discrete representation of entropy, if you like.
In the real-case scenario, choose a very small, tiny distance d (I would say less than the average distance between two molecules in your coffee), and comparing two snapshots of your coffee at any two moments, you will find at least one molecule whose position on snapshot 2 is at a distance less than d from its position on snapshot 1. But it's actually more of a statistical result, even though Brouwer himself got the idea while stirring his coffee.",12

,,,,,,,,z135f1xgisbejb01t22nxb4welygffsat04.1475228122411732,The Evil Neoliberal,7 months ago,1476525310875,"aleph n is only defined for n being an ordinal number. Ordinals are basically a generalisation natural numbers, usually defined as an equivalence class (or representative of an equivalence class) of well ordered sets. A well ordered set is any totally ordered set (basically something ordered the way you would expect) with the additional property that every non empty subset contains a least element (that is, if you select arbitrarily many arbitrary elements you can find one of them that is the smallest). The integers with the usual <= are not an ordinal, since the negative numbers, for example, do not contain a smallest element. However, there exists a well ordering of the integers, for example 0 1 2 3 .... -1 -2 -3 -4 ... in which case aleph -1 would be huge.",0

When I take the number 7 and multiply it with n where n = 0 to 9 and write the result down as two digits
i.e.  00
       07
       14 .... etc
Then add the two digits together to make 10 single digits I end up with. 075 418 6429
Where I'm from, that's a working phone number. It doesn't work with any other number, only 7.
So after class I called the number, out of curiosity.
A recording played saying that my phone was now blocked and that I would have to call my service provider to get it working again.

z12thxpwbtz0ufull23hv12rqxeagpreb,The Evil Neoliberal,7 months ago,1476525332024,"The example with stirring the coffee doesn't work:
If you move the spoon right through the centre you'll move some amount of coffee towards the side of the cup. Upon ""hitting"" the boundaries, some part of the coffee will move to the left and some to the right side of the cup, meaning you essentially ""cut"" some of the coffee. Therefore stirring (unless stirring just means moving the spoon in a circle) is not a continuous function.

Imagine all of the molecules were rotated around the center by 90 degrees. None of them would be in their original locations except for the middle column of molecules. if you then took the spoon and dragged it across the diameter, the middle ones would have been moved out of their original position, and it's entirely possible for none of the other molecules to have gone back to their original position, because you've effectively cut the relationship. The math and theory is still correct, but stirring coffee is not a correct example because it falls into one of the caveat conditions of the mathematical theory.",0,false,0,,,,,,

z12qen5jawnfh1uj104cihnjqqzlsh1jbdc,Sagiri,7 months ago,1476525349368,"Noting that four is the only fixed point in terms of counting the letters that spell it (meaning that applying that operation recursively will loop forever) doesn't in and of itself guarantee that you'd end up at four regardless of your starting point. For example, 0 and 1 are fixed points of exponentiation, but you don't end up in an infinite loop of 0 or 1 when you repeatedly square a number.

It's possible that there's a non-looping infinite sequence of integers (or, more likely an infinite number of families of infinite sequences) that you could enter instead. Of course, maybe this has been proven not to happen, but it's possible in principle.",0,false,0,,,,,,

However the coffee mixing is not entirely accurate, I think. Actually coffee is a liquid, which means that it can be transformed in a non continuous way, molecules in the coffee are free to move away from each other allowing other molecules to fill up the space. If you imagine a connected ball of coffee initially inside the coffee filled mug, you can split it with a spoon and put one half away from the other, resulting in your transformation function having a non connected image of a connected set, thus the function is not continuous and the fixed point theorem doesn't apply.",0,false,0,,,,,,

the theorem only works with continuous space, not with pixels that have fixed boundaries.
if you just made it 6x6 blocks and rotated it, not a single field would light up.


And the mixing isn't true either.
Simplify it - lets say you have just 2 balls in the cup - move them a bit around - it is very very unlikely that either of them goes back to its exact original position.
With liquids you of course have a couple billion times more atoms to consider, so higher chance due to that, but you also have a vastly bigger possibility realm.
if it wasn't due to uncertainty, you could even go as far as to say that not a single particle would ever go back to any of its previously held positions.",0,false,0,,,,,,

z13ugfugos32zlb3b23gsnpxzuitijpry04,kennkong61,7 months ago,1476525396633,"A channel with 10M+ subscribers should be more careful about the accuracy of what they publish, especially one which is trying to teach people something.
This video is so riddled with errors I hardly know where to begin.
Let me take the Borsuk-Ulam theorem.  In order for it to be true, both temperature and pressure must vary continuously over the surface of the earth, but neither do.  Regions of different temperatures and pressures are separated by boundary layers that meteorologists call fronts.  Since the assumptions of the theorem are violated, the application of the theorem is invalid.
I knew you were going to hit one of my pet peeves the moment you mentioned infinity.  Aleph Null is not a number.  No operations valid for numbers are defined for it, not even equality.  Furthermore, any infinite sequence at n terms is different from the infinite sequence less one term at n terms by the difference between the first and nth terms, for any and all n, so they are only equal when the first and nth are equal.  In a monotonically decreasing sequence, this is never true. So Aleph subscript infinite aleph is not equal to Aleph subscript [infinite less one|warning: this expression is undefined, too] aleph for both reasons.
The coffee stirring example is wrong for the same reason as the Borsuk-Ulam example, coffee is not continuous.  I give you credit for noting that coffee isn't continuous, but a collection of particles.  But I give you failing marks for continuing.  A theorem which isn't true for discontinuities isn't true.  There is no such thing in logic as almost true.
But for the sake of argument, let's pretend coffee is a continuous substance.  Putting the spoon in it is a discontinuous deformation.  So is taking the spoon out.  If some of the coffee sticks to the spoon when you take it out, its a cut.  If a drop of that liquid falls off the spoon back into the coffee, that's a paste.  And let's not forget the water vapor that escaped while you were stirring.",0,false,0,,,,,,

,,,,,,,,z13shp5qdvzxjjl0a22mgvcy2rvyvf00z.1475138720372579,MegaCake1234,7 months ago,1476525416849,"That temperature and pressure thing requires a one other thing: Time to freeze, this assumed in the therom

The idea of the theorm is that if time is frozen (although same approach could in theory be done if tested while moving around Earth at fastest speeds to make temperature and pressure changes impossible to do), then no changes can take place that damage this idea while the test proceeds. How it works is as you move the thermometer around the Earth at some point the temperatures must change to reflect each other, if so there is a point where they were both the same. Then the same is applied for the crossing area of all those points (logic dictates a ring should be made around the Earth of all points) with pressure, and basically its guaranteed that there will always be a point where this is true on Earth.",0
,,,,,,,,z13shp5qdvzxjjl0a22mgvcy2rvyvf00z.1475139556784922,Eltyo,7 months ago,1476525416852,"If you're mathematically minded, the Borsuk-Ulam is basically an application of the Intermediate Value Theorem. This is my understanding of it though:

You start at thermometer A (let's say it has 20 degrees) and travel around the earth until you get to thermometer B (10 degrees). 

The key here is taht while you are travelling there is always a point directly opposite you on the other side of the earth (a.k.a your antipode).

While you are travelling your temperature reading will start at 20 degrees and eventually get to 10 degrees when you reach thermometer B.

While you are travelling the point opposite you will start at 10 degrees and eventually get to 20 degrees when it reaches thermometer A.

Your temperature reading starts off being greater than your antipode's temperature reading right? But at some point your temperature reading will eventually be less than your antipode's temperature reading, because your final reading is 10 degrees (when you reach thermometer B) and your antipode's final temperature reading will be 20 degrees (when it reaches thermometer B). 

Right before that point in time when your temperature is less than your antipode's temperature is when you have exactly the same temperature reading as your antipode. 

Idk if I've just confused you more, but whatever.

Also in regards to the digital thermometer, I think in the situation Michael describes, the thermometer is assumed to be a perfect instrument.",0
,,,,,,,,z13shp5qdvzxjjl0a22mgvcy2rvyvf00z.1475374553290198,Zach Kutzer,7 months ago,1476525416855,"I understand the math and why and how this works. What I'm arguing is, yes at some point while moving the two thermometers, there will be a point at which they have the same reading on opposite sides of the planet. Creating the X in the graph shown in the video. But that doesn't mean the places the thermometers are at the time of that reading (The very middle of the X) are the same.

Thermometer (B) could read 10 degrees and while you're moving the thermometer (B) to a place that is 8 degrees, it will pass 9 degrees, and the opposite thermometer (A) also reads 9 degrees as that place actually is 9 degrees, but the place that thermometer (B) is, isn't 9 degrees, its 8 degrees. The thermometer simply needs to pass the 9 to get to the 8 from the 10.",0
,,,,,,,,z13shp5qdvzxjjl0a22mgvcy2rvyvf00z.1475381712003855,Eltyo,7 months ago,1476525416860,"So you say:

""But that doesn't mean the places the thermometers are at the time of that reading (The very middle of the X) are the same.""

This theorem says nothing about the thermometers being in the same position, rather the thermometers are always at antipodal positions. The X in that graph represents the point at which their temperatures are the same, not their locations. It's a graph of temperature over time, not location over time.

Also, just a side note, if B passes 9 degrees, it has to at some point have a reading of 9 degrees, because it is moving continuously.",0

z12wuzmpmzujd3auv223w5pxwt3ljlu5j04,pluto,7 months ago,1476525438976,"Hi Vsauce, you suggest that there are always antipodal points on Earth with equal temperature and equal pressure. This seems true only in the case that an isotherm or isobar happens to have precisely corresponding antipodes to itself, allowing the Borsuk-Ulam Theorem to be used again. I do not see how math would prove this true with two continuous variables considered independently the way you described. It could just be a rare coincidence. However with that argument, it then seems highly unlikely, and can be conceivably false. I watched the other videos on the Borsuk-Ulam Theorem from the links in the dooblydoo of your video and I am still not convinced of the proof method described. However, if elevation change is possible, then any path can be isobaric by changing the elevation. There can then be a forced set of isobaric antipodes to work with, and the statement becomes true. Still, it is difficult to technically discuss temperature and pressure separately because they are related by the ideal gas law.",0,true,1,,,,,,
,,,,,,,,default-z12wuzmpmzujd3auv223w5pxwt3ljlu5j04.1475127974880985,EnteiFire4,7 months ago,1476525438981,"Take f(x) = T(x) - T(-x), where T(y) is the temperature at the point y and -y is the antipode of the point y. Of course, f is continuous.

Take ANY starting point a, and take ANY path from a to -a and apply f to every point in that path.

If T(a) = T(-a), then we've found our antipodes with the same temperature! Cool!
If T(a) < T(-a), then f(a) < 0 and f(-a) > 0.
If T(a) > T(-a), then f(a) > 0 and f(-a) < 0.

According to the intermediate value theorem, we conclude that there is a point c of the path where f(c) = 0 and therefore T(c) = T(-c).

As the video explains, since ANY path has that point c, we conclude that there is a line of points that goes around the Earth where the antipodes have the same temperature. However, it doesn't mean that all those points have the exact same temperature! The proof for the pressure is the same as above, using the specific path where the antipodes have the same temperature.",0

However, the sun does reflect off all the moon dust. I'm sure you agree with that because that's how we are able to see the moon. All of that reflected light makes it nice and bright on the surface of the moon. So you tell your camera to only pick up really bright stuff so that your photos look correct. You do this by making the hole known as the aperture really tiny; the same way your pupil gets really small when everything around you is bright. Stars, in comparison are so dim that they don't show up on film or video at the same time as a bright lunar surface. There's a great episode of Mythbusters that set up a really good experiment demonstrating this. It's also really worth watching.",2

,,,,,,,,z12bst0ooyypcbnix04cf3ur2tnyhvf5d2w.1475120092364199,verdatum,7 months ago,1476525554516,"+Bin Ghannam
The lunar surface is more reflective than most regions on earth. So stars can't particularly be seen unless you took the time to look up and allow your eyes to adjust. That's how you're able to see the north star in the morning. You look up at the sky at a part of the sky that is away from the sun, and you let your eyes adjust until you can see it. When they were in shadow, the astronauts have stated they were able to see stars, but they didn't take photos when they were in shadow, because...it'd be dark. Makes sense, right?

If they happened to care, they could have pointed their camera at the sky, adjusted the aperture nice and small and take a nice long exposure, and they could've taken wonderful photographs of stars. But they weren't worried about satisfying a bunch of people decades in the future with unfamiliarity of optics and photography. They were interested in investigating the moon :)",0

¬†Regarding your sun at dawn: On earth, when the sun is low, it becomes dimmer because the light passes through a greater amount of atmosphere. This is amplified in the winter months because of the earth's tilt. On the moon, because there is no atmosphere, you have neither of those effects. As long as the sun is all the way up in the sky, it's the same brightness level whether it is lunar-dawn, lunar-noon, or lunar-sunset. z12lxlabruytv3z0n23vfhcp0ly1sfcyw04,The Man-Witch of the West,7 months ago,1476525573502,"I wonder if similar idempotent chains exist in other languages.  With Japanese it depends how you write the number.  Hiragana, romaji or kanji.  Or katakana, I suppose, but why use those for numbers?  Anyway, with kanji, a longer number in terms of characters within the Arabic numeral system that we use in English won't necessarily increase the number of kanji, or if it does, not by much.  For example, 10000, man, has one character in kanji, 100,000, jiu-man would use two, as would 1000,000, hyaku-man.  But then after 10,000,000, sen-man we reach the next order and a new, singular kanji because the Japanese numbering convention is based around systems of ten thousand.  A more complex number, however, would use more kanji.  10,003, for example, is man-san, which is two kanji.  Then 11,283 would be man-ichi-sen-ni-hyaku-hachi-ji-san.  Which would be seven or eight kanji, depending on if you include ichi (1) in reference to the number of thousnds (sen) or not.  In either case, the number of kanji is lower than ten, so would itself be one kanji, which then loops.  With a complex number of more than ten kanji, it would reduce to either two or three, which reduces to one, which repeats.  Nothing special there; of course one loops in this instance.  With hiragana and katakana, it would function a little differently.  San, meaning three, consists of two characters; sa and n.  Then two is ni, which is one.  Ichi is two; i and chi, so it loops between one and two.  Ten thousand, hyakuman consists of hi(ya), ku, ma and n.  This reduces to four which is either shi or yon; which go to one and two respectively and establish the loop.  Even 11,283 would do this; consisting of 14 or 15 characters, depending on if you count the ya as seperate to the hi in hyaku.  It could also be 12 or 13 if ichi is omitted.  Jiu-ni, jiu-san, jiu-yon and jiu-go consist of 3/4 or 5.  Which enter the ichi-ni-loop.  With romaji it would loop at san or ni.

Anyone who responds to this please do something similar with Spanish, then nominate a language for the next person.",0,false,0,,,,,,

z134sbjx2xb4ddhe523dz1xzlubydfxwk04,George Wang,7 months ago,1476525578516,"your algorithm for recursive alephs is incorrect.

Because the subscript of every aleph (_) is the main input/variable, that means that it would have to end on the right/bottom-most, and not on the left/top-most script. for it to end on the right would mean that a countably infinite number of steps had to be taken to reach an aleph with a countable subscript (aleph [with no subscript] by itself does not denote any particular infinity), which had to be the input in the first place for the recursive algorithm. the algorithm's construction would have to end in the first place to receive the input, so it wouldn't be endless and thus it couldn't be countably infinite number of infinities.

your algorithm and reasoning reminds me of the colloquial proof for .999... = 1, which is that if you take .9 from .999... and .9 from 1 and multiply both sides by ten, you get .999... = 1. this is incorrect. you cannot take .9 from .999... because subtraction/arithmetic starts from the lowest decimal place, and you cannot get to the lowest decimal place with .999... (.999... doesn't end with a digit that is 9; it doesn't go 999... ...9, that would be an incorrect construction of a number - it doesn't end). 
the rigorous proof is by geometric series, the value of sum(rx10^-n, n to infinity) = 1/(1-r) for r=.9 = 1, but its construction is a countably infinite series of decimal places all equal to nine and it doesn't end, thus .999...

you have to start with a finite input and finite construction, and your algorithm isn't a finite construction.",0,false,0,,,,,,

z12tij5hvv3hcj1zl04chrfzpw30ttuxqbo,flamespirit919,7 months ago,1476525598541,"7:22
I learned that formula in one of my engineering classes a couple days ago. It's called Newton's Method. If you want to find the point where two lines intersect you repeatedly use the formula x-(f(x)/f`(x)) until the answer is continuous
Where:
x=Initial guess and subsequent answers
f(x)=Your original formula
f`(x)=The derivative of the formula

If you wanted to find sqrt(16), then you would have y=sqrt(16). However, for the formula to work, your function must be equal to 0. It has to be 0 because the formula is meant to find where the line tangent to the specified point crosses the x-axis. So we get y^2-16=0. So now f(x)=x^2-16. Plugging in these values to the formula we get:
g(x)=x-((x^2-16)/2x)
You can simplify this to get:
g(x)=(x+(16/x))/2
Where 16 is the number you want to find the square root of.

If you plug in any value and then plug the answer into the formula again, the answer will get closer and closer to the value you need. So if we use 3, we'll get the following answers:
g(3)=4.167
g(4.16666666667)=4.003
g(4.00333333333)=4.00000138773
g(4.00000138773)=4
g(4)=4",0,false,0,,,,,,

Surely it is possible for each molecule to be in a different position after stirring. z12ivlejqvisg1cjf04cjv2oeqjeevnxasc0k,LordMardur,7 months ago,1476525648469,"Talking about fixed points and iterations, the banach fixpoint theorem is interesting (not sure if that's what it is called in english). If you have an infinite domain with a norm (e.g. euclidean space) and a continuous transformation of that domain into itself, which is also a contraction, then this contraction has exactly one fixed point. Any starting point will converge to that fixed point when the transformation is applied repeatedly. The shown square root algorithm is basically that, a continuous contraction of the (positive) real numbers onto themselves. That the square root is a fixed point is trivial to see. One only has to show that it is a contraction to conclude, that the algorithm always works.",0,false,0,,,,,,

,,,,,,,,z125vb1olkjuvlnck22idjaquprnyxgze04.1475175992451221,OverkillRabbit,7 months ago,1476525689189,"+Thomas Anderson
You do know that both expressions are equivalent, right?
Whether you say that 25 represents 2*10+1*5 or 10*2+5*1 does not matter. The inherent commutative property makes the distinction trivial. It is also not a matter of formal accuracy, as both are equally accurate descriptions of the number. The fact that we use base 10 does not matter. It also would not matter in binary, or base 2. They share the same basic mathematical axioms.

Your incompetence to understand that the distinction is trivial is neither my fault, nor an actual issue of any sorts. It is merely you not overcoming mental barriers that only you uphold for yourself.",1

,,,,,,,,z124ujtweyafx53h404cirnapwmks1dojo40k.1475099805009167,Elliot N,7 months ago,1476525712075,"You've also overgeneralized the fixed point property. In Calculus you'll learn what a continuous function is and how the Intermediate Value Theorem explains this phenomenon. Unlike temperature on the Earth, the distribution of mass/energy in space is not continuous, as you can have a large amount (say, 100) of mass at one point and a small amount of mass at a point directly next to it (say, 5), without needing to pass through every value between 100 and 5 as you move between the points. The only way for there to assuredly be an identical Earth planet in the universe is for the universe to be infinite, which is countered by the limit of the speed of light and therefore the size of the observable universe.",0
,,,,,,,,z124ujtweyafx53h404cirnapwmks1dojo40k.1475100027375913,Adam Thornton,7 months ago,1476525712077,"This only means that there is a point somewhere in the world that has the same temperature and pressure as its antipode, it doesn't mean that any specific point does. Also, this argument applies to closed surfaces, and we don't really know the shape of universe on a large scale.",0
,,,,,,,,z124ujtweyafx53h404cirnapwmks1dojo40k.1475100468884983,LordMardur,7 months ago,1476525712080,"If you start arguing particles, then temperature is not continuous either. Temperature is the average thermal energy of the molecules in a region. You can think about gravity or material density in the same way. E.g. if you define material density at any point as the number of nuclei in a small sphere around that point divided by the volume of the sphere, then you will have a continuous function within the resolution of ""one nucleus"".

If you take two points in space and any two distinct curves between those points (that would be the two half circles connecting the two antipodes in the earth example), then any continuous function must have two points (one on each curve) with equal value even under an additional location constraint (e.g. the points also must be antipodes). If does work everywhere. On the earth surface, inside the volume of a room, in space, everywhere. It only has to be a finite space.

The problem with ""there MUST be another earth somewhere"" is about dimensions. The earth surface is (in the simplified model) two dimensional. That is why you can get two continuous functions to match. If you take 3d space, you could expand that to (any) three continuous functions which will have a pair of points in space (with an additional positional constraint) where all 3 values are the same on both points. The ""earth"" is defined by bazillions of atoms in specific configurations. That is more than 3 scalar values can describe. So no second earth for you.",0
,,,,,,,,z124ujtweyafx53h404cirnapwmks1dojo40k.1475119556727061,Chris Bernard,7 months ago,1476525712082,"+The Sethioz Project you didn't reply with any real rebuttal... I never said anything against the existence of dark matter nor the particle, I only pointed to an anomaly that counterattacks the possibilities of the theorem holding true for the whole universe. You didn't even explain anything really, you just babbled about dark matter, and reiterated a few things I said in different ways. 

I was pointing to the necessity of continuous entropy in a closed system for this to work, not just interaction. Not only is there many other ways that this just isn't a proof, and I only specified one using the actual theorem because I didn't want to seem like I was just against the hypothesis you made, but, as you can see how everyone has explained, the theorem isn't going to prove another earth. Apart from the premise that that's simply not what the theorem would do even if it proved successful, there's just way too many other things that break the hypothesis down. In case of success, a point between two other points match up in temperature and pressure, but that point isn't pre-determined, so that would just lead to one bit of space matching attributes of one other bit of space, and maybe just possibly another bit of matter matching the environmental attributes of another bit of matter, but not a whole specified planet. This is all assuming you can even look at the universe with the same perspective as a Planet. The best way to prove another earth is just probability like I was pointing to before.

,,,,,,,,z12ogfl5nq3xc51mn23pspzo3wrphdwto.1475098089924434,Chris Bernard,7 months ago,1476525716970,"You're right in the case that the hole would displace molecules, and because of this hole, there is not only a geometric hole, but a cut in another perspective (2 different things happen in 2 dimensions). Which means you're right over +KohuGaly, but this would have to be a complete hole all the way to the bottom of the cup to work. 

Still skeptical? Think about a snapshot of the swirling drink from above, and you can imagine seeing a small indent, which means there are some points that are drastically moved apart, but imagine looking at the cup from the side and outlining the parts where the liquid would be.. It would still be occupying a good bit of space completely regardless of the intent atop. Now imagine you swirled so hard that there's a hole all the way down to the bottom, you know this is a hole from a bird-eye point of view, but now looking at it from the side, imagining that you could move forward looking through the (vertical) layers of the liquid from the side. At some point you would see two separate outlines depicting the liquid, and since they are separated this would indicate a cut through the liquid. 

Tldr look at vsauce's cup figure/picture 3:02, a spin hard enough to create a hole would look exactly the same. I don't think it works that well with 3d objects, but vsauce was betting that no matter what it would be easy to say it works because the hole in 3d is the same as his hole in 2d, just also able to be seen in another perspective as what it really is (a cut) and the different horizontal layers work just like 2d. He was really betting on the middle staying the same in parts furthest away from the transformation (the stirring), which would start from the top and have less effect at the bottom of the cup.",2

,,,,,,,,z12ogfl5nq3xc51mn23pspzo3wrphdwto.1475179042827288,Chris Bernard,7 months ago,1476525716984,"+dubsterNL‚Äã the best chance for the theorem to hold is a middle spot furthest away from the transformation (stirring) which would mean that the bottom middle molecules would have a pretty good chance of sitting in the same place and maybe even just some bottom molecules, but if you can spin it so hard it actually creates a parting all the way down to the bottom then this immediately kills the best chance of a molecule when settling in a different spot. 
It's a lot weirder than the 2d explanation because the transformation is caused by physics like centripetal force and cohesion of the liquid as well as just the way liquid takes shape of it's container, which means it's very much like the 2D visualization, but also just capable of a lot more. But even theoretically that hole would bypass the theorem because of the possibility of displacement. 

+RStarbuck13‚Äã nice bro, technically there's still a chance that a molecule still ends up in the same place, but that's almost random chance and since the theorem holds that there will be a spot that matches and the hole makes that impossible to prove. Cool thing is that the inside wall of liquid still holds the middle molecule, which means that when you stop spinning and the liquid starts displacing back to the middle, there's a chance that the middle molecule falls back into place (it's just that possibility is also true for at least a few other molecules around the part, which negates the theorem), depending on how large the part is at that (horizontal) ""layer"".",1

First shrink the board so it's smaller than 1 colored square of the larger board then rotate 180.  Let's look at the green on the first column, third row and its adjacent yellowish color.  Align the smaller board so that the border between the yellow and green is shared, but the green overlaps the yellow and vice versa. z12dyhwx1wi3dvgoa04cefzj0tj2v5yxfw00k,ellieban,7 months ago,1476525760785,"Wait, though, isn't stirring coffee more like cutting and pasting? If I rotate the coffee in the mug by n <180 degrees, then the only point the coffee hasn't moved is the axis of rotation. If I then move that column of coffee sideways, allowing an equal amount to flow back into the space it occupied, then none of the coffee is where it started. The rule breaks down, because the surface of the coffee isn't a fixed boundary, the coffee can heap up around the spoon and then settle somewhere non-contiguous to where it started... I think... Although I'm sure, this being V-sauce, I'm wrong and I just don't know why.",0,true,1,,,,,,
,,,,,,,,default-z12dyhwx1wi3dvgoa04cefzj0tj2v5yxfw00k.1475094518733642,Doc Daneeka,7 months ago,1476525760789,"When you let the coffee flow sideways and back into the space it occupied, I think the fixed point (points in this case) are the lines right at the edges of the cup if you draw a diameter along the line it is flowing (if I am visualising your description correctly) The rule definitely does not break down if you stick to the conditions: a the function must be continuous and the set compact and convex. If the coffee is a cylinder, it's convex, is it compact though? Thats where the mathematics and reality separate. The fixed point 'lines' I just mentioned are right on the boundry. If the 'set' (all points of coffee) includes those points on the boundry then yes it works. But we can make it not work by saying those points on the boundry are not part of the coffee, in which case it obviously does not work, but importantly it stoped working because the cylinder without its boundry points is not compact, so it's still perfectly consistent with the rule!",0

z12zebvyirnjxravv22mt3z5zrz2uvguq,ljfa,7 months ago,1476525770461,"I guess the example with the map is better explained by Banach's fixed point theorem rather than Brouwer's. At least that's the common example for Banach's fixed point theorem.
Banach's fixed point theorem states that any continuous mapping that makes distances between points smaller (more precisely, there is some positive number less than one such that the distance between any two mapped points is at most that number times the distance between the original points) has exactly one fixed point. This does not require boundedness or no holes, just a nonempty complete metric space.
So actually, even when the map is crumbled up or folded, there will be no more than one point lying on the point it represents.",0,false,0,,,,,,

z13mxt5hqlu1vhc1o232tbxommacuxy3e,Libor Tinka,7 months ago,1476525785856,"The fixed point theorem appears in construction of a class of fractals named IFS (Iterated Function Systems). These fractals are described by a set of transformations leading to a fixed point, which is the fractal itself. This has been used in fractal image compression since we keep only small number of transformations and can use any starting image at any resolution and always end up with the target (decoded) image after few iterations.

The JPEG lossy image compression, for example, is designed to be idempotent, hence if you recompress an already compressed image (with same quality settings), no information is loss, the quality will stay the same.

Image descriptors in computer vision are often designed to be invariant to various geometric transformations, hence images can be matched and aligned to each other regardless on how they are moved, rotated or zoomed.",0,false,0,,,,,,

With respect to your video showing the reality of fixed points, why have we not been able to find a point (an origin) at which we can refer to always and use as a coordinate plane for everything in need of one ve it space or not but, you know, so that it's standardized?",1,true,4,,,,,,
,,,,,,,,z12birdyktusevbjp04cg13zoxvrjvcjbr00k.1475090200007305,Jakob Stubbs,7 months ago,1476525791395,Trying to sound extra smart to make daddy proud?;),1
,,,,,,,,z12birdyktusevbjp04cg13zoxvrjvcjbr00k.1475093142016493,Eric V,7 months ago,1476525791396,I'm trying to make Harambe proud,1
,,,,,,,,z12birdyktusevbjp04cg13zoxvrjvcjbr00k.1475093551950403,Doc Daneeka,7 months ago,1476525791399,"Because that's not what the fixed point theorem says

In an inertial frame, the coordinate points don't move. Inertial things have a constant velocity wrt an inertial coordinate system, that velocity can be zero, and for any inertial thing you can pick a frame where it's velocity is whatever you like, 0 or otherwise. 

Fixed points are a concept from an area of mathematics called Topology. The idea is that if you take a set with certain properties and make a function that takes points from the set to other points in the set with certain properties, there will always be a point that gets mapped to itself. Exactly which point depends on the function, it does not mean any function will have the same fixed point as any other.

Usually when you model space as a 4d coordinate system (space + time), you assume it is infinitely big, and let's say you are ignoring special relativity and use galilean relativity (velocities are much smaller than the speed of light! and space is euclidean!) The fixed point theorem he mentioned in the video only works for 'compact' sets, and in normal settings the enitre infinte 3d euclidean space is not compact (it's not bounded) so there's nothing to say a map (like a gallilean change of coordinates) has a fixed point.",1

When an object, such as a spacecraft, constantly accelerates in a vacuum, after exactly two hours it's speed in kilometers or miles per hour always equals the distance it has traveled or displaced in those units. Example: if a spacecraft accelerates at one g (9.85 meters per second squared) after two hours it will reach a speed of 250,000 kilometers per hour at a distance of 250,000 kilometers. This ratio holds true whatever the acceleration rate is. At 10 g (98.5 meters per second squared) after two hours the ship is traveling at 2.5 million kph at a distance of 2.5 million kms. z12zsrixwqmgufz1l222flhi0lzufjx4v04,Ole Hansen,7 months ago,1476525827140,"I am not convinced that the stirring of coffee is analogous to a continuous transformation. The feature that distinguishes continuous transformations from the other types of transformations is that any two points that are neighbors before the transformation will remain neighbors during and after the transformation. (That's why cut/paste is not allowed.)

The stirring of a liquid seems to break this rule. While there is likely groupings of molecules, that are still together after stirring, I don't see a reason to assume that every molecule will remain in proximity to its original neighbors - and so the theorem does not apply.",0,false,0,,,,,,

Yes, any number this function is applied to enough times will converge to FOUR, but the fact that FOUR is the only number in English spelled with as much letters as the value it represents does not give you this yet. 

Suppose we have a dialect of English where 5 is spelled out as FIV. If we start with SIX, we get THREE, which goes to FIV, which goes to THREE, and so on. 

Any number in regular English converges to FOUR because it is the only LOOP (in this case of length 1).",0,false,0,,,,,,

We can get stuck in the same cicle with the number ocho (8), because it also has cuatro letters, and cuatro has seis letters and so on. The same with tres (3), and with uno (1, and uno has 3 letters), and with dos (2, the same as one), and others.

Let's try a different number, 7: siete has five letters and cinco (5) has 5 letters also. Nueve (9) also has 5 numbers, so right now we know that in sanish there can be two different cicles.

Let's try a bigger number: 1 000 000, un millon has 8 letters, and then it is in the first cicle. Dos millones (2 000 000) has eleven letters, and once (11) has also four letters, so it fits in the first cicle. Let's pick something more random, let's say dos mil setecientos ochenta y cuatro (2 784)and it has 31 letters,  and treinta y uno has 11 letters... also fits in the first one.

z12qg1qi1qzjgzjl3233int40puwerbgq04,Stochastic,7 months ago,1476525916116,"You didn't finish the proof for the 9, I find it quite interesting.
1) It has to stay in ‚Ñï_0: it starts in ‚Ñï by definition, and the most you can subtract from n is n, if and only if it is a one-digit number. Then it hits 0, and it is fixed there.
2) It always decreases, because you're subtracting a positive quantity from a positive quantity.
 We can infer that, repeating the process long enough, every natural number n will reach 0
3) Every number that you get in the process has to be a multiple of 9 in each step but the first one
 To sum it up:
If it's more-than-one-digited, it won't hit 0 straightaway, but it will eventually. You have to pass from a one-digit number. That number has to be 9, because it's the only one-digited number that is multiple of 9. 
So every natural number has to get to 0 and has to get there passing from 9",0,false,0,,,,,,

If a person counts all the whole numbers (0, 1, 2, ... ), what do they get? Also, an infinite amount of numbers. However, this set contains one number more than the infinite set of natural numbers. 

Now, let's think about integers ( ... , -2,  -1 , 0 , 1, 2, ...). This also contains an infinite amount of numbers, however, it includes other numbers that the prior two sets do not contain. 

How about real numbers? Those include ALL numbers from negative infinity to positive infinity, not JUST integers. This is also an infinite set, and includes more numbers that all the other sets I've mentioned.

using namespace std;
int main ()
{
 float temp,temp1,num,result;
 int a;

    result=temp;

z135yzsydy2ky3tlw23vc1rgfoicvd1mq,Skyrone Dyrone,7 months ago,1476525985746,"Awwwww... although your description of the number 25 is mathematically equivalent.  It isn't how it is in a base-10 numbering system.  The first digit to the left of the decimal point is the number of times that you have 10 to the zero-th power (or ones).  The second position is the number of times you have ten to the first power (or tens).  The third position is the number of times you have ten to the second (or hundreds)... and so forth.  Each place is one power of ten larger than the previous that is closer to the decimal point. All of this is obvious as we all just know.

Thus 25 is more accurately 2 times 10 to the first power (10+10) plus 5 times 10 to the zero-th power (the zero'-th power of any base number 2 or greater is always 1... so 5 times the zero-th power of 10 is equal to 5).

Mathematically 2 ten times is the same as 10 two times. But, when trying to explain the number we know as 25, it is best to use the poper way that expresses the digits of the number in its base number notation.

A complicated subject as Fixed Points mixed in with this kind of under sight, to me, dilutes the discussion and validity for me to a consider the concept of Fixed Points.  To me, if one of the foundation building blocks of a concept is fundamentally wrong, I can't proceed with what is proposed farther down the line. That was when the video ended for me.",0,false,0,,,,,,

- Rotate it 180 degrees
- Resize and make it smaller until a 4x4 of the coloured squares is as big as or smaller than one of the original squares
- Move it to the top left.
- Position it in such a way that the original top left square is to the bottom right of where it used to be, and line up the borders exactly.
- The 4x4 starting from the bottom right in the original should now be fully in the top left square.
There you go, not a single square is where it used to be!

,,,,,,,,z122i1zb4wevvjyej225tze5brbpxf4pg04.1475077226765527,Alex Larsen,7 months ago,1476526101725,"There is no infininest infinite infinity. The number of ways you can make a subset of a set, will always be strictly larger than the number of elements in the set. Pick any infinity, and let's call it A. Then consider the number of ways you could make a subset of a set of A elements. That number will be strictly larger than A.

Specifically, you can make 2^n different subsets from a set with n elements. For any cardinal w, infinite or not, it holds that w < 2^w. For example, it even holds for 0:
0 < 1 = 2^0",1
